 class relations became displaced onto the figure of the Chinese labor immigrant who struggled for inclusion at a time when black freedmen were fighting to redefine citizenship.Racial Reconstruction demonstrates that U.S. racial formations should be studied in different registers and through comparative and transpacific approaches. It draws on political cartoons, immigration case files, plantation diaries, and sensationalized invasion fiction to explore the radical reconstruction of U.S. citizenship, race and labor relations, and imperial geopolitics that led to the Chinese Exclusion Act, America's first racialized immigration ban. By charting the complex circulation of people, property, and print from the Pacific Rim to the Black Atlantic, Racial Reconstruction sheds new light on comparative racialization in America, and illuminates how slavery and Reconstruction influenced the histories of Chinese immigration to the West.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aAfrican AmericansxHistoryx19th century. 0aAfrican AmericansxHistoryy19th century. 0aAmerican prose literaturexHistory and criticismx19th century. 0aAmerican prose literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aChinesexHistoryx19th centuryxUnited States. 0aChinesezUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aEmigration and immigration lawxHistoryxUnited States. 0aEmigration and immigration lawzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aLabor movement in literature. 0aNational characteristics, American, in literature. 0aWorking class in literature. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Discrimination & Race Relations.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP / FUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311071187540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479899043423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781479899043.jpg  a978-3-11-071187-5  NY